### [FAIL] [SPEC/TODO DRIFT] — todo.md Phase C still says `Promise.allSettled`, spec says `Promise.all` + outer try/catch
**Where:** todo.md L100 (Phase C bullet): "Internal: `Promise.allSettled([sendOne(user), sendOne(admin)])`-Pattern wo `sendOne` = `sendMail`-call + audit-emit-after-resolution." vs. spec.md L249 which shows `await Promise.all([...])` inside `try/catch`.

**Gap:** R2 Finding #6 was resolved in spec.md by switching to `Promise.all` + outer `try/catch` (which is semantically distinct from `Promise.allSettled` — the former rejects if any arm rejects, the latter never rejects). The two patterns have different failure modes. Generator reading todo.md as the implementation-plan will write `Promise.allSettled` (which doesn't need an outer try/catch and changes the semantics of the per-arm `sendOne` `.catch()` shape). spec.md is canonical, but generators traditionally drive off todo.md.

**Implementation hazard:** Generator implements `Promise.allSettled([sendOne("user"), sendOne("admin")])` per todo.md, omits outer try/catch (because allSettled "never rejects"), then DK-6 sub-test (todo.md L49 — `auditLog` throws → `sendSignupMails` resolves) becomes a coincidence-pass rather than a structural-defense. Spec/todo discrepancy will trip Codex in PR-R1.

**Suggested fix:** Update todo.md L100 to read: "Internal: outer `try { await Promise.all([sendOne(user), sendOne(admin)]) } catch { /* swallow */ }` mit per-arm-`sendOne`-try/catch (siehe spec §M2a-C code-snippet)." Aligns terminology with spec.

---

### [FAIL] [TEMPLATE FIDELITY / CORRECTNESS] — Subject-line goes through HTML-escape path; subjects are RFC 2047, not HTML
**Where:** spec.md §M2a-B render-rule L114–115: "HTML-Output: subject = `interpolate(template.subject, formDataEscaped)` mit `formDataEscaped = mapValues(formData, escapeHtml)`."

**Gap:** Mail subjects are NOT HTML — they are MIME-encoded RFC 2047 headers, rendered as plain text by every mail client. HTML-escaping the subject means a user named "O'Brien" gets the admin-notify subject "Neue Mitgliedschafts-Anmeldung: Anna O&#39;Brien" — visible HTML-entities to the recipient. Same trap with `&` (becomes `&amp;`), `"` (becomes `&quot;`), and umlauts if the escape function ever extends to combining marks. Currently `escapeHtml` only touches 5 chars, but `'` and `&` are common in real names.

The `text` output already uses raw `formDataRaw` (correct). But there's only ONE `subject` field — same string for both `text` and `html` outputs. So either:
- Spec's `formDataEscaped` for HTML-subject is wrong (recipient sees entities).
- Or `subject` should be split into `subjectText` and `subjectHtml` (overkill — real mail-clients always render subject as text).

DK-5 structural assertions don't catch this — they assert "subject contains 'Mitgliedschaft'" not "subject preserves apostrophes verbatim".

**Implementation hazard:** Phase-2-Smoke admin opens the very first member-notify mail, sees "Anmeldung: Anna O&#39;Brien" in his Inbox-subject. Looks broken. Real-world impact bounded but visible-to-stakeholder.

**Suggested fix:** spec.md §M2a-B render-rule clarification: "**Subject is NEVER HTML-escaped** in either output — it's an RFC 2047 MIME header rendered as plain text. Both `subject` outputs use `interpolate(template.subject, formDataRaw)`. Only the `html`-body interpolation uses `formDataEscaped`." Update DK-5 to add: "subject of admin-notify with `formData.nachname=\"O'Brien\"` is `\"Neue Mitgliedschafts-Anmeldung: Anna O'Brien\"` (raw apostrophe, NOT `O&#39;Brien`)."

